def get_config():
    with open("config.yaml", 'r') as stream:
        config = yaml.safe_load(stream)
    return config
#Load Depression By Income Level

DepressionByIncomeLevelPath = (config['DepressionByIncomeLevel'])

def GetCountryNameByCode(code):
    country = pycountry.countries.get(alpha_2=code)
    if(country):
        return country.name
    elif code =="UK":
        return "United Kingdom"
    elif code =="EL":
        return "El Salvador"
    elif str.startswith(code,"EU"):
        return "European Union"
    else:
        return "NotFound"

#Add Country Name based on country code
DepressionByIncomeLevel["Country"] = [(GetCountryNameByCode(geo)) for geo in DepressionByIncomeLevel.geo]
DepressionByEducationLevel["Country"] = [(GetCountryNameByCode(geo)) for geo in DepressionByEducationLevel.geo]

def BarPlotForIncomeLevel(groupColumn,year,func, sorter):
    avg = DepressionByIncomeLevel.groupby(groupColumn).agg(average = pd.NamedAgg(column=year,aggfunc=func))
    avg.reset_index(inplace=True)
    if(sorter == "Groups(Ascending)"):
        avg.sort_values(groupColumn,inplace=True, ascending = [True])
    elif(sorter == "Groups(Descending)"):
        avg.sort_values(groupColumn,inplace=True, ascending = [False])
    elif(sorter == "Group Values(Ascending)"):
        avg.sort_values("average",inplace=True , ascending = [True])
    elif(sorter == "Group Values(Descending)"):
        avg.sort_values("average",inplace=True , ascending = [False])

    p = figure(x_range=avg[groupColumn], height=350, width=1050, title= groupColumn + " depression distribution("+ year+")" , toolbar_location=None, tools="")
    p.vbar(x=avg[groupColumn], top=avg.average, width=0.9)
    p.xgrid.grid_line_color = None
    p.y_range.start = 0
    p.xaxis.major_label_orientation = math.pi/8

    # Calculate Standard deviation when it is mean 
    import numpy as np
    if(func == "mean"):
        stdDf = DepressionByIncomeLevel.groupby(groupColumn).agg(np.std)
        xs = avg[groupColumn]
        ys = avg["average"]
        yerrs = stdDf[year]
        err_xs = []
        err_ys = []
        for x, y, yerr in zip(xs, ys, yerrs):
            err_xs.append((x, x))
            err_ys.append((y - yerr, y + yerr))
        # plot them
        p.multi_line(err_xs, err_ys, color='red')
    p.yaxis.axis_label = func + " depression level (%)"
    return p
    
groupData = ["age","sex","Country","IncomeQualtile"]
years = ["Value2014","Value2019"]
func = ["mean","max", "min"]
sorter = ["Groups(Ascending)", "Groups(Descending)", "Group Values(Ascending)","Group Values(Descending)"]
selectGroupColumn = pn.widgets.Select(name='Group By:', options=groupData)
selectYear = pn.widgets.Select(name='Show Data For Year:', options=years)
selectFunc = pn.widgets.Select(name='Aggregation:', options=func)
selectSorter = pn.widgets.Select(name='Sort By:', options=sorter)
interact1 = pn.interact(BarPlotForIncomeLevel, groupColumn= selectGroupColumn, year = selectYear,func= selectFunc,sorter= selectSorter)
interact1

#convert income quantile and education level to int values to be able to make some comparisons
def getQuantileNo(quant_inc):
    if(quant_inc =="QU1"):
        return 1.0
    elif(quant_inc =="QU2"):
        return 2.0
    elif(quant_inc =="QU3"):
        return 3.0
    elif(quant_inc =="QU4"):
        return 4.0
    elif(quant_inc =="QU5"):
        return 5.0
    elif(quant_inc =="TOTAL"):
        return 0.0
DepressionByIncomeLevel["IncomeQuantileInt"] = [getQuantileNo(quant_inc)for quant_inc in DepressionByIncomeLevel.IncomeQualtile]
def getEducationLevelNo(level):
    if(level =="ED0-2"):
        return 1.0
    elif(level =="ED3_4"):
        return 2.0
    elif(level =="ED5-8"):
        return 3.0
    elif(level =="TOTAL"):
        return 0.0
DepressionByEducationLevel["EducationLevelInt"] = [getEducationLevelNo(educationLevel)for educationLevel in DepressionByEducationLevel.EducationLevel]

DepressionByIncomeLevel = DepressionByIncomeLevel.drop(DepressionByIncomeLevel[DepressionByIncomeLevel.Value2014.isna()].index)
DepressionByIncomeLevel = DepressionByIncomeLevel.drop(DepressionByIncomeLevel[DepressionByIncomeLevel.Value2019.isna()].index)
DepressionByIncomeLevel["Value2014Rounded"] = DepressionByIncomeLevel["Value2014"].astype(int)
DepressionByIncomeLevel["Value2019Rounded"] = DepressionByIncomeLevel["Value2019"].astype(int)


DepressionByEducationLevel = DepressionByEducationLevel.drop(DepressionByEducationLevel[DepressionByEducationLevel.Value2014.isna()].index)
DepressionByEducationLevel = DepressionByEducationLevel.drop(DepressionByEducationLevel[DepressionByEducationLevel.Value2019.isna()].index)
DepressionByEducationLevel["Value2014Rounded"] = DepressionByEducationLevel["Value2014"].astype(int)
DepressionByEducationLevel["Value2019Rounded"] = DepressionByEducationLevel["Value2019"].astype(int)

DepressionRate2014 = pd.merge(DepressionByIncomeLevel, DepressionByEducationLevel, on=['age','sex','Country',"Value2014Rounded"] )
DepressionRate2019 = pd.merge(DepressionByIncomeLevel, DepressionByEducationLevel, on=['age','sex','Country',"Value2019Rounded"] )
DepressionRate2014 = DepressionRate2014[['IncomeQuantileInt','sex','age','Country','Value2014Rounded','EducationLevelInt']]
DepressionRate2019 = DepressionRate2019[['IncomeQuantileInt','sex','age','Country','Value2019Rounded','EducationLevelInt']]

Now for same rounded depression rates among same age groups and same sexes in same countries we are going to check if is there a direct (or maybe reverse) relation between income and education level?

import numpy as np
def BarPlot(func, sorter,country,age):
    groupColumn = "IncomeQuantileInt"
    avg = DepressionRate2014[(DepressionRate2014.Country == country)&(DepressionRate2014.age == age)].groupby(groupColumn).agg(average = pd.NamedAgg(column="EducationLevelInt",aggfunc=func))
    avg.reset_index(inplace=True)
    if(sorter == "Groups(Ascending)"):
        avg.sort_values(groupColumn,inplace=True, ascending = [True])
    elif(sorter == "Groups(Descending)"):
        avg.sort_values(groupColumn,inplace=True, ascending = [False])
    elif(sorter == "Group Values(Ascending)"):
        avg.sort_values("average",inplace=True , ascending = [True])
    elif(sorter == "Group Values(Descending)"):
        avg.sort_values("average",inplace=True , ascending = [False])
    p = figure(x_range=avg[groupColumn].astype(str), height=350, width=1050, title= "mean education level based on income quantiles for 2014 for same values of depression" , toolbar_location=None, tools="")
    p.vbar(x=avg[groupColumn].astype(str), top=avg.average, width=0.9)
    p.xgrid.grid_line_color = None
    p.y_range.start = 0
    p.xaxis.major_label_orientation = math.pi/8
    p.yaxis.axis_label = func + " Education Level"
    p.xaxis.axis_label = "Income Quantiles"
    
    return p
